		{"id":"1e04d5ca5bef5006","type":"text","text":"**`RAID 1`** : It use the concept of `mirroring` to store the data meaning `raid disk 1` data is copied to `raid disk 2` and so on. So all the `raid disk` contain same data\n\n1. `suppose we have raid disk /dev/sda1 , /dev/sdb1 , /dev/sdc1` also while making `raid partition disk` we give `fd` instead of `8e` for type because `fd` is for `raid`\n2. `mdadm -C /dev/md0 -l 1 -n 2 /dev/sda1 /dev/sdb1`\n\t1. `-l 1` represent `RAID 1`\n\t2. `-n 2` represent `2 disk`\n3. `cat /proc/mdstat` it will show the details also it will show `disk 1` is `syncing` with `disk 2`\n4. `mdadm --detail /dev/md0` it will show brief details of `RAID 1 /dev/md0`\n5. `mkfs.ext4 /dev/md0` formatting the raid\n6. `mkdir /radi1`\n7. `mount /dev/md0 /raid1`\n8. `df -hT`\n9. `cd /raid1`\n10. `touch file{1..100}.txt`\n\n***NOTE*** : Here Making one disk faulty does not mean to lost of data permanently. Because both disk contain same data so on failure of one disk we can restore data from another disk just we need to add new disk to `raid 1`","x":-650,"y":-240,"width":780,"height":600,"color":"1"},
		{"id":"0dafb4f70624ce46","type":"text","text":"***How to fail or fault the disk in `RAID`***\n\n1. `mdadm /dev/md0 -f /dev/sda1`\n\t1. here we are failing disk `/dev/sda1`\n\t2. `cat /proc/mdstat` it will show `F` in front of `sda1 disk` meaning faulty disk\n2. `mdadm --detail /dev/md0` it will show complete information like faulty disk, how many used to make `RAID` also `RAID level` which is `1` etc.\n\n**How to replace faulty disk**\n1. first unmount the disk\n\t1. `umount /raid1`\n2. `mdadm /dev/md0 -r /dev/sda1` \n\t1. `-r` remove \n3. `mdadm /dev/md0 -a /dev/sdc1` here adding new disk\n4. `cat /proc/mdstat` it will show `syncing data` from `/dev/sdb1` to `/dev/sda1`\n5. `mdadm -D /dev/md0`\n\t1. `-D` or `--detail` is same thing\n6. `mount /dev/md0 /raid1`\n7. `cd /raid1`\n8. `ll` you will see our data. even though one disk is failed still our data has not lost","x":160,"y":-240,"width":780,"height":600,"color":"1"},
